{
  format: 1
  name: namespace-signature-type-mismatch-rejected
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#host-namespaces", "#expressions", "§16.2", "§16.5"]
  note: '''
    §16.2: the load-time descriptor supplies "function names and typed
    signatures" for each namespace function, and "every used function has a
    known type ... and pinned contract." The descriptor declares
    util.double : (int) -> int, but the mutation body calls util.double(@label)
    where @label is a text parameter. The argument type does not match the
    pinned signature, so the typed namespace contract is violated.

    Firing point (why a scenario, not a static case): a mutation program body
    is the ONE legal position for an app-registered namespace call (§16.5), and
    a mutation body is parse-only at load and admitted per call. The typed
    contract is therefore enforced when the mutation runs — the descriptor's
    pinned `(int) -> int` signature refuses a text argument at admission — not
    at load. Driving the call is what makes the mismatch assertable at its real
    firing point; the signature is stated in this case's hosts descriptor, so
    the expected rejection is deducible here rather than from an implementation.
    (The pure load-time counterpart — a signature mismatch validated by the
    checker before admission — is unit-tested by liasse-expr
    `host_calls::argument_type_mismatch_is_rejected`.)
  '''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.sigmismatch@1.0.0"
    $requires: {
      util: "test.util@1"
    }
    $model: {
      items: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "text"
        n: "int = 0"
      }
      $mut: {
        // util.double expects int; @label is text -> typed-signature violation
        "add({ id: text, label: text })": [
          "d = util.double(@label)"
          "row = .items + { id: @id, n: d }"
          "return row { id, n }"
        ]
      }
      $public: {
        items: { $view: ".items { id, n }", $mut: { add: ".add" } }
      }
    }
  }

  hosts: {
    namespaces: [
      {
        id: "test.util"
        version: "1.2.0"
        interface_hash: "ih-util-1"
        functions: {
          double: { signature: "(int) -> int", effect: "pure", op: "double" }
        }
      }
    ]
  }

  steps: [
    // The mutation admits and runs its body; util.double(@label) is a text
    // argument against a pinned (int) -> int signature, so the typed namespace
    // contract fails at admission and the call is rejected — no row is written.
    { call: "public.items.add", args: { id: "x", label: "hello" }
      expect: { outcome: rejected, violates: ["#host-namespaces", "#expressions"] } }
  ]
}
